":["(2007: 216; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wood  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 312, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]},{"name":"Bois","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcide, Antoine, Donat, Marcel, Ovide, Ovila, Raoul, Serge.","French: topographic name for someone living or working in a wood, from (Old) French <i>bois</i> ‘wood’ (from Late Latin <i>boscum</i> ‘bush, shrub, undergrowth’, of ancient Germanic origin), or a habitational name from (Le) Bois, the name of several places in various parts of France. This surname is also found in Haiti. Compare   Debois   and the most frequent French form   Dubois  . Compare also   Boie  ,   Boies  , and   Boyce  .","English: variant of   Boyce   and   Boyes  ."]},{"name":"Woods","meanings":["English: variant of   Wood   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted as a translation of <b>Ó Cuill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coll</i>’ (see   Quill  ), or in Ulster of <b>Mac Con Coille</b> ‘son of <i>Cú Choille</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the wood’, which has also been mistranslated   Cox  , as if formed with <i>coileach</i> ‘cock, rooster’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Alice Wood of Spaxton was born in 1440, in Wybunbury, Cheshire, England, her father, Sir Robert George Wood of Cheshire, was 11 and her mother, Lady Joyce Clarke, was 5. She married Sir Roger Hill in 1470, in Wybunbury, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1480, in Houndstone, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40, and was buried in Houndstone, Somerset, England."},"et":{"1440–1480":"1440–1480","1428–1493":"1428–1493","1470–1532":"1470–1532","1475–Female":"1475–Surnud","1478–1580":"1478–1580","1479–1511":"1479–1511","1483–1570":"1483–1570","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1435–1480":"1435–1480","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1570":"1570","1493":"1493","1470":"1470","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","1479":"1479","1435":"1435","1478":"1478","1511":"1511","1455":"1455","1532":"1532","1476":"1476","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1475":"umbes 1475","1428":"1428","1449":"1449","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, England","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England","Wrinehill,Wybunbury,Cheshire,England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1440–1480":"1440–1480","1428–1493":"1428–14